Predicting Fat Content of Meat

The fat content is an important characteristic of meat. The reliable but cumbersome method to establish the fat content is via analytic chemistry. A much quicker method to measure the fat content of meat could be based on near-infrared (NIR) absorbance spectra. To evaluate the aptness of NIR-based method for fat measurement, finely chopped pure meat samples with different fat contents were analysed with respect to their near infrared (NIR) absorbances. Absorbance of a 100 channel spectrum of NIR (wavelength range 850 â€” 1050 nm) were recorded as -log10 of the transmittance. As gold standard, the fat content was determined by analytic chemistry and is given in percent. For further details on the data we refer to the publication Â«Optimal Minimal Neural Interpretation of SpectraÂ» by Borggaard and Thodberg (1992).

The task is to predict the fat content of a meat sample on the basis of its NIR absorbance spectrum. In real applications, the analysis of NIR-spectra is challenging and there is a wide range of analysis strategies.1 These strategies typically involve dimension-reduction steps like principle component analysis (PCA) and make use of non-linear models like neural networks to infer chemical information (like fat content) from NIR-spectra. Here in this assignment it will do to apply different linear models with possibly some shrinkage involved.

Linear Model

  • Fit an additive model with intercept and all available NIR-predictors on the training data and store the model fit as nir_lm. We will use this model as a reference in our benchmark of different models. You do not need to name all features that take part in the regression as predictors. The formula fat ~ . specifies variable fat as response and the . on the right hand side is a shortcut referring to all remaining variables in the dataframe that you specify via data=.
  • Look at the model summary. What are the statistically significant predictors (at a 5% significance level)?

Solution

We use the standard R-function lm to fit the full additive model. This means, we include all NIR-features but do not include any interactions between the features. Only the main effects are modelled. To this end, we use the . abbreviation of the formula interface:

It is a long model summary because we have 100 NIR-based predictors, plus intercept. Generally, the estimated coefficients of the NIR-predictor reach from -87 to 62. This means, when an individual NIR-feature is changed by one unit and all other NIR-features are held constant the model predicts a change in fat that lies in this range! This is remarkable as the output variable fat is measured on a percentage scale and within the training data, the observed fat ranges only between 0% and 50%. So, the predicted effects of the individual NIR-wavelengths must cancel out each other. We observe that the sign of the parameter estimates frequently changes for adjacent NIR-wavelengths. Generally, positively correlated predictors (e.g., predictors of neighbouring NIR-wavelengths) have negatively correlated predictor coefficients in a linear regression model. This is because the predictors Â«competeÂ» for explaining change in the outcome variable. The negative correlation is reflected in the variance-covariance matrix of the estimated predictor coefficients, in particular the elements one off the main diagonal are predominantly negative in our full additive model fit:

In this full linear model, only 4 predictors (NIR48, NIR40, NIR55, NIR31) are significant at the 5%-significance level.

Variable Selection

All absorbance predictors are potentially relevant predictors for fat-level and hence the full linear model seems like the best linear additive model. Nevertheless, we try out two variable selection methods to build two simpler regression models.

Using AIC

The R-function step uses â€” starting from the provided model fit â€” the AIC-criterion to decide if dropping or adding a variable improves the model. The AIC-criterion balances model fit on the training data with model complexity. Lower values of AIC indicate better fits. For a fitted model with \(p\) parameters, AIC is defined as \[ \operatorname{AIC} = -2 \times \text{max. log-likelihood} + 2\times p \] The negative log-likelihood part quantifies the model fit while \(+ 2\times p\) is a penalty for model complexity. Many statisticians consider the AIC to be a better criterion to decide which predictors to drop/add than the F-statistic that you have seen in the lecture.

With argument direction="both" in the step-function we specify that at each step of the variable selection the variables that were dropped in previous steps are re-considered for inclusion in the model again (why could this be useful?). At each step, intermediate model fits are printed. As this is too verbose in our case we switch that off with the argument trace = 0.

Here, we will not consider all model candidates that occur in intermediate steps but retain only the final model of the stepwise selection procedure on the training data. This is why we do not need the validation data set.

  • Store the final output model of AIC-based variable selection on the training data. Later, we evaluate this model fit on the reserved test data.
  • How many predictors have been retained in the final model after AIC-based stepwise variable selection?
  • Why can it happen that a feature variable that was dropped in a previous step is added again in a later step?

Solution

We do variable selection with the R-command step. By default, it uses the AIC-criterion for variable selection. In each step, that variable is dropped (or re-added) that yields the biggest reduction in AIC.

# trace=0 to suppress lengthy output of intermediate steps
fm_nir_step_AIC <- step(nir_lm, direction = "both", trace = 0)

We use trace=0 to suppress intermediate model output. The final model has retained 53 NIR-features. This is 53% of the original NIR-features. Looking into the summary we see that through the reduction in predictors the model now finds 30 significant predictors (at the significance level of 5%) which is more than before in the full model. In other words, by dropping redundant (this is: highly correlated) predictors we gain statistical resolution. But the estimated coefficients of the retained NIR-predictors are still large in absolute value which raises doubts if this model produces stable predictions.

During the variable selection procedure, feature variables that were dropped in previous steps are also reconsidered to be added again (default argument direction="both" of step). This is reasonable because it is possible that a predictor variable \(X\) seems uninteresting at first but only because it is clouded by other predictors in the model. Once these are taken out eventually, the predictor \(X\) might improve the model again. In other words, there is no such thing as a single parameter estimate in a multiple (linear) model: it all depends on which other parameters are in the model as well. During the AIC-based variable selection, a predictor variable reappears in 0 steps.

Using BIC

The degree how strongly model complexity is penalized in variable selection can be varied. Using the factor \(2\) in the penalization term \(2\times p\) gives the AIC, but we can also choose to be more stringent. The Bayesian information criterion (BIC) (also known as Schwarz information criterion as it was proposed first by Gideon E. Schwarz in 1978) uses a factor \(\ln(n)\) for the penalization term where \(n\) is the number of training data. Hence, when there are at least \(n=8\) training data, BIC in general leads to sparser models than AIC.

  • Use the parameter k= of the step-function to adjust the penalization factor to get BIC instead of AIC as variable selection criterion. Confirm that the resulting model is sparser than the model selected by AIC.
  • How many predictors in the BIC-model are statistically significant at the significance level of 5%?

Solution

We use BIC for variable selection with step when we set parameter k= to \(\ln(n) = 5.0876\).

fm_nir_step_BIC <- step(nir_lm, direction = "both", k = log(nobs(nir_lm)), trace = 0)
summary(fm_nir_step_BIC)

The BIC-selected model contains 12 parameters (including the intercept). During the BIC-based variable selection, a predictor variable reappears in 1 steps. 11 of the 11 retained predictors are statistically significant at the significance level of 5%. Again, we see that dropping even more less-important predictors leads to an further increase in statistical resolution. Interestingly, from the 4 NIR-features that were significant in the initial full linear model only NIR40 are also retained in the BIC-model and are significant in that model as well.

Shrinkage Methods

Variable selection either keeps a variable or drops it completely from the model, â€” it is either-or. The R-package glmnet allows for different ways to continuously shrink parameter coefficient estimates of a linear regression model. The main functions of the package are glmnet and cv.glmnet.

Within these functions the parameter alpha= specifies the type of continuous penalization:

  • alpha=0 corresponds to ridge regression.
  • alpha=1 is Lasso-regression.
  • a value between 0 and 1 corresponds to a mixture of ridge and Lasso-regression and this approach to penalization is called elastic net.

glmnet and cv.glmnet will by default fit models for a whole range of values for the penalization parameter Î», ranging from high penalization (with intercept only model as extreme case) down to very mild penalization that approaches the full unpenalized linear model.

In the lecture, we used a separate validation data set to choose an optimal penalization parameter Î». Here, we make use of cross-validation (CV) through the function cv.glmnet: The training data is divided internally into ten equally-sized folds. Each fold is used once in turn as validation data while the remaining nine folds serve as training data. As a result, we get for each value of Î» ten prediction error estimates for \(\operatorname{Err}_{\mathcal{T}}\), calculated as mean squared error. The cv.glmnet-object contains the mean of these ten cross-validated errors (entry cvm) and the estimate of its standard error (entry cvsd) for each value of Î». For model selection, you can choose that value for the penalization parameter Î» that minimizes the mean cross-validation error (entry lambda.min) or â€” as the authors of the glmnet package recommend â€” choose the largest value of penalization parameter Î» such that the cross-validated prediction error is within one standard error of the minimum (entry lambda.1se). Doing so we acknowledge that the cross-validated prediction errors are estimates and we rather take a simpler model with a stronger penalty that has a comparable error to the best performing model.

cv.glmnet does already the recommended centring and scaling of the predictor variables for you (via its default argument standardize=TRUE) so that you do not have to do it manually. But unfortunately, glmnet does not support the formula interface that we have come to appreciate with lm and we have to prepare the data as response vector and predictor matrix:

# glmnet works with vectors and matrices (and, alas, not with the formula interface)
# training data
y_train <- nirData_train |> dplyr::pull(fat)
x_train <- nirData_train |> dplyr::select(!fat) |> as.matrix()
  • Use the function cv.glmnet from the glmnet-package to fit penalized regression models. This function chooses a sequence of candidate values for the penalization parameter Î». This default is fine for us here, â€” you do not need to specify your own sequence via parameter lambda=. Also, please do not use function glmnet with a single value for lambda=. The object returned by cv.glmnet has all information needed. Concretely, fit three different models in the given order:
    1. Ridge regression
    2. Lasso-regression
    3. Elastic net as mixture of ridge and Lasso-regression, with mixing parameter Î± = 0.3. (With Î± = 0.3, we choose a stronger contribution of ridge regression because we have so strongly correlated predictors where ridge regression is designed for.)
  • Identify for each of the three models classes the value for the penalization parameter Î» so that the cross-validated prediction error is within one standard error of the minimum prediction error. Use coef on the respective cv.glmnet-object.
  • How are the model coefficients affected by the penalization? Compare the estimated coefficients with those from the full linear model.

Solution

We use the function cv.glmnet three times to fit the three model classes. cv.glmnet-objects come with their own plotting routine that highlights the value of Î»min that minimizes the mean squared error in cross-validation and the value Î»1SE that yields a cross-validated prediction error is within one standard error of the minimum.

Note that the exact result of cv.glmnet also depends on the state of the pseudo-random generator because the cross-validation uses a random allocation of folds. In this assignment, we set the seed initially as shown in the beginning and fit first ridge regression, then lasso and finally elastic net.

# load glmnet-package (needs to installed once before on your computer)
library("glmnet")

fm_nir_ridge_cv <- cv.glmnet(x = x_train, y = y_train, alpha = 0)
fm_nir_lasso_cv <- cv.glmnet(x = x_train, y = y_train, alpha = 1)
fm_nir_elnet_cv <- cv.glmnet(x = x_train, y = y_train, alpha = .3)

coef_nir_ridge_cv <- coef(fm_nir_ridge_cv, s = "lambda.1se")
coef_nir_lasso_cv <- coef(fm_nir_lasso_cv, s = "lambda.1se")
coef_nir_elnet_cv <- coef(fm_nir_elnet_cv, s = "lambda.1se")

par(mfrow = c(1, 3)) # three base-plots in a row
plot(fm_nir_ridge_cv, main = "Ridge")
plot(fm_nir_lasso_cv, main = "Lasso")
plot(fm_nir_elnet_cv, main = "Elastic net")

As Î»1SE, we get

  • 1.29091 for ridge regression,
  • 0.0486 for Lasso regression and
  • 0.04013 for elastic net (with fixed mixing parameter Î± = 0.3).

The parameter estimates for all the NIR-features move closer to zero, although the selected penalization parameters Î»1SE are rather small for all three models, which corresponds to low penalization.

In ridge regression with Î»1SE=1.29 we see a drastic effect on the estimates of the model parameters: the coefficient estimates for the NIR-predictors range from -5.5 up to 8 which is a way shorter range than the range of the coefficient estimates of the full linear model -86.6 up to 61.7. In ridge regression, none of the estimated predictors are really zero, though.

With Lasso, the coefficients range from -35.8 up to 45.9. This is a wider range for the coefficients than with ridge regression. But the L1-penalization forces 88 of the NIR-feature coefficients to be zero. A coefficient of zero means that the predictor is effectively dropped from the model. This highlights the built-in variable selection property of Lasso-regression.

With elastic net (Î± = 0.3), 47 of the predictors are dropped. The coefficients range from -15.6 up to 26.2, a shorter range than when using pure L1-penalization.

Model Assessment

We have fitted different models on the NIR-training data. Now, we want to use the reserved test data to assess these models.

Rank the six models based on the mean squared error they achieve on the test data. Use predict to get the model prediction for new data. Check the help-pages for the relevant predict-functions: see ?predict.lm and ?predict.cv.glmnet. For the shrinkage-models from glmnet-package you need to prepare the test data as response vector and predictor matrix as glmnet-package does not support the formula interface.

y_test <- nirData_test |> dplyr::pull(fat)
x_test <- nirData_test |> dplyr::select(!fat) |> as.matrix()

modelPerf <- c(
  # lm-models
  lm=mean((y_test - predict(nir_lm, newdata = nirData_test))^2),
  step_AIC=mean((y_test - predict(fm_nir_step_AIC, newdata = nirData_test))^2),
  step_BIC=mean((y_test - predict(fm_nir_step_BIC, newdata = nirData_test))^2),
  # glmnet-models
  ridge=mean((y_test - predict(fm_nir_ridge_cv, newx = x_test, s = "lambda.1se"))^2),
  lasso=mean((y_test - predict(fm_nir_lasso_cv, newx = x_test, s = "lambda.1se"))^2),
  elnet=mean((y_test - predict(fm_nir_elnet_cv, newx = x_test, s = "lambda.1se"))^2)
)
Model Performance as mean squared prediction error (MSE) on test data
Model Class Test Error Rank
elnet 11.51 1
lasso 11.63 2
step_BIC 16.31 3
step_AIC 24.98 4
ridge 26.25 5
lm 31.09 6

We store the mean squared error \(\operatorname{Err}_{\mathcal{T}}\) for each of the six models in a vector and we display the results in a table. We rank the models according to the test error. In this example, elastic net shows the smallest prediction error on test data and it is hence the best of the studied models for this data set. Ridge regression and the full additive model perform the worst on the test data even if this method was designed to work with correlated predictors.

But please do not generalize too quickly. The model prediction performance really depends on the problem at hand and you better check the performance of your models for each data modelling task afresh.

Machine learning infrastructure in R

Model building and selection is a big topic in machine learning. There are at least three packages that in fact provide a whole framework to do model selection and model assessment in R.

  1. modelr â€“ a lean package to help you create pipelines when modelling, in particular useful for resampling methods. Development of this package has been mostly suspended in favour of the tidymodels package.
  2. tidymodels â€“ a collection of packages for modelling and machine learning using tidyverse principles. Personally, I find the wealth of tidymodels-packages exuberant.
  3. mlr3 â€“ Â«machine learning in RÂ». It is a well-designed package that covers many aspects of machine learning. It uses a different programming style from tidyverse.

In particular the last two packages define a unified programming interface to the different steps needed for statistical model building strategies. The advantage is that the framework covers a vast number of different model classes and fitting routines. Ridge regression and Lasso are just two of the supported regression models, further supported models are random forests, neural networks or support vector machines.

Have a look at the package homepages to get an idea how they work. It is definitely worth it to learn one of these frameworks if you want to do more machine learning in R.
